<https://w3id.org/pink> <http://data.europa.eu/r5r/status> "Under Development" .
<https://w3id.org/pink> <http://purl.org/dc/terms/abstract> "The PINK Annotation Schema provides the semantic basis for SSbD.\n\nThe PINK Annotation Schema expands on the annotation schema provided by tripper, which again expands on the DCAT-AP.\n\nA reference documentation of terms reused from standard W3C vocabularies can be found https://pink-project.github.io/PINK-annotation-schema/widoco-reused-terms/index-en.html.\n"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink> <http://purl.org/dc/terms/bibliographicCitation> "xxx" .
<https://w3id.org/pink> <http://purl.org/dc/terms/contributor> <https://orcid.org/0000-0003-4250-4584> .
<https://w3id.org/pink> <http://purl.org/dc/terms/created> "2025-09-08" .
<https://w3id.org/pink> <http://purl.org/dc/terms/creator> <https://orcid.org/0000-0001-8869-3718> .
<https://w3id.org/pink> <http://purl.org/dc/terms/creator> <https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1560-809X> .
<https://w3id.org/pink> <http://purl.org/dc/terms/creator> <https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1849-5246> .
<https://w3id.org/pink> <http://purl.org/dc/terms/creator> <https://orcid.org/0000-0002-8053-8198> .
<https://w3id.org/pink> <http://purl.org/dc/terms/hasFormat> <https://www.w3.org/TR/turtle/> .
<https://w3id.org/pink> <http://purl.org/dc/terms/license> "https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/legalcode" .
<https://w3id.org/pink> <http://purl.org/dc/terms/publisher> <https://pink-project.eu/> .
<https://w3id.org/pink> <http://purl.org/dc/terms/title> "PINK Annotation Schema"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink> <http://purl.org/ontology/bibo/doi> "tbd" .
<https://w3id.org/pink> <http://purl.org/ontology/bibo/status> <http://purl.org/ontology/bibo/status/forthcoming> .
<https://w3id.org/pink> <http://purl.org/vocab/vann/preferredNamespacePrefix> "pink" .
<https://w3id.org/pink> <http://purl.org/vocab/vann/preferredNamespaceUri> "https://w3id.org/pink" .
<https://w3id.org/pink> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#priorVersion> "0.0.0" .
<https://w3id.org/pink> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#versionInfo> "0.0.1" .
<https://w3id.org/pink> <http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/homepage> <https://github.com/PINK-project/PINK-annotation-schema> .
<https://w3id.org/pink> <http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/logo> <https://tess.elixir-europe.org/system/content_providers/images/000/000/777/original/pink-logo-orange-colorB-500.png> .
<https://w3id.org/pink> <https://w3id.org/widoco/vocab#introduction> "\nThe PINK Annotation Schema has a modular structure and aims to cover the following features:\n\n* Allow to categorise resources (datasets, models, software, etc) according to their SSbD dimensions and categories/sub-categories.\n* Provenance, based on the [PROV-O](https://www.w3.org/TR/prov-o/) ontology. PROV-O is fully adapted by the PINK Annotation Schema, having the three top-level PROV-O classes, *Activity*, *Entity* and *Agent* in root.\n* Extension of the basic PROV-O provenance to complex scientific workflows with spatial and temporal parts.\n* Allow documentation of workflows that have not (yet) been executed. Such documentation is done at class-level. When executed individuals should be created for the evaluated activities and their input and output providing a full PROV-O provenance graph.\n* Top-level taxonomy for (advanced) materials and chemicals based on [EMMO](https://emmc.eu/emmo/) with mappings to [ChEBI](https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/) for chemicals.\n* Categorisation models.\n* Strong taxonomy for relations, which are grouped into:\n  - [parthood relations](https://pink-project.github.io/PINK-annotation-schema/docs/background.html#parthood-relations), based on mereology\n  - [causal relations](https://pink-project.github.io/PINK-annotation-schema/docs/background.html#causal-relations), based on causality\n  - [semiotic relations](https://pink-project.github.io/PINK-annotation-schema/docs/background.html#semiotic-relations), based on [Pierse semiotics](https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/peirce-semiotics/)\n\nSeparate reference documentations exists for the following sub-modules:\n\n* [ddoc](https://pink-project.github.io/PINK-annotation-schema/widoco-ddoc/index-en.html): The Tripper data documentation vocabulary, with terms reused from other ontologies and vocabularies. Mainly [Dublin Core](https://www.dublincore.org/specifications/dublin-core/dcmi-terms/), [FOAF](http://xmlns.com/foaf/spec/) and similar basic vocabularies.\n* [reused-terms](https://pink-project.github.io/PINK-annotation-schema/widoco-reused-terms/index-en.html): Additional reused terms by the PINK Annotation Schema ([DCAT](https://www.w3.org/TR/vocab-dcat-3/), [PROV-O](https://www.w3.org/TR/prov-o/), etc).\n* [matter](https://pink-project.github.io/PINK-annotation-schema/widoco-matter/index-en.html): Taxonomy for (advanced) materials and chemicals\n* [models](https://pink-project.github.io/PINK-annotation-schema/widoco-models/index-en.html): Taxonomy for models.\n\nThe root of the PINK Annotation Schema is shown below. More information can be found in the [background](https://pink-project.github.io/PINK-annotation-schema/docs/background.html) section.\n\n"@en .
