# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#Interpreter
<https://w3id.org/pink#Interpreter> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Interpreter> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#Agent> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Interpreter> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "The agent that connects the sign to an entity in a semiotic (meaning-making) process."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Interpreter> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "A person (interpreter) that measures the length (sign) of an pencil (object)."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Interpreter> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Interpreter"@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#LongData
<https://w3id.org/pink#LongData> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#LongData> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <https://w3id.org/pink#IntegerData> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#LongData> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#seeAlso> <https://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema11-2/#long> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#LongData> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "A data representing a 64-bit integer number."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#LongData> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "LongData"@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#MaterialProcess
<https://w3id.org/pink#MaterialProcess> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#MaterialProcess> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <https://w3id.org/pink#Process> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#MaterialProcess> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "A process that has material as input and output."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#MaterialProcess> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "MaterialProcess"@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#Matter
<https://w3id.org/pink#Matter> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Matter> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#Entity> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Matter> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "An entity that possess mass and occupies volume."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Matter> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Matter"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Matter> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote> "From the definition it follows that matter is an object with fermionic parts."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Matter> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote> "The interpretation of the term \"matter\" is not univocal. Several concepts are labelled with this term, depending on the field of science. The concept mass is sometimes related to the term \"matter\", even if the former refers to a physical quantity (precisely defined by modern physics) while the latter is a type that qualifies a physical entity.\nIt is possible to identify more than one concept that can be reasonably labelled with the term \"matter\". For example, it is possible to label as matter only the entities that are made up of atoms. Or more generally, we can be more fine-grained and call \"matter\" the entities that are made up of protons, neutrons or electrons, so that we can call matter also a neutron radiation or a cathode ray.\nA more fundamental approach taken here, considers matter as entities that are made of quarks and leptons, without excluding particles like the W and Z bosons that possess some mass, but are not fermions. This definition also include antimatter."@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#Measurement
<https://w3id.org/pink#Measurement> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Measurement> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <https://w3id.org/pink#Process> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Measurement> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "An observation that results in a quantitative comparison of a 'property' of an 'object' with a standard reference based on a well defined mesurement procedure."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Measurement> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Measurement"@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#Model
<https://w3id.org/pink#Model> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Model> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <https://w3id.org/pink#Sign> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Model> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "A useful simplified description of a selected part of the world."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Model> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "Newton's law of motion is a model for how a body will move when subjected to forces.\nA mouse can be seen as a model for a human (e.g. in medicine).\nAn architectural floor plan is a model of a house.\n"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Model> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Model"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Model> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote> "A model is a sign that resembles or imitates an object, in shape, function or by sharing a similar logical structure."@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#NumericalData
<https://w3id.org/pink#NumericalData> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#NumericalData> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <https://w3id.org/pink#SymbolicData> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#NumericalData> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "A symbolic data representing a numerical value."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#NumericalData> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "NumericalData"@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#Object
<https://w3id.org/pink#Object> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Object> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#Entity> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Object> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#altLabel> "Continuant"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Object> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#altLabel> "Endurant"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Object> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "An entity that has a temporal extension."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Object> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Object"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Object> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote> "Object individals will typically also be an individual of 'Matter'. However, when categorising something as an 'Object', the focus is on its existence (throughout one of more processes), while 'Matter' focuses on that it pocess mass and takes up volume and how it can further be categorised as "@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Object> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote> "Object is the class of all individuals who's temporal parts are of the same type as the whole."@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#Participant
<https://w3id.org/pink#Participant> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Participant> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#Agent> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Participant> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <https://w3id.org/pink#Object> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Participant> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "An object that participates to a process."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Participant> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "A student during an examination. The student exists both before and after the examination."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Participant> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Participant"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Participant> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote> "Mereologically participation means that the object is a spatial part of the process."@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#Process
<https://w3id.org/pink#Process> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Process> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#Activity> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Process> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#altLabel> "Occurent"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Process> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#altLabel> "Perdurant"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Process> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "An activity with temporal parts."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Process> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Process"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Process> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote> "The temporal parts of a process are not of the same type as the process itself."@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#Property
<https://w3id.org/pink#Property> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Property> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <https://w3id.org/pink#Sign> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Property> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "An \"atomic\" sign that stands for an physical interaction with an object."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Property> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Property"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Property> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote> "A property is atomic in the sense that is aimed to deliver one and one only aspect of the object."@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#ReliabilityDocument
<https://w3id.org/pink#ReliabilityDocument> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#ReliabilityDocument> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/Document> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#ReliabilityDocument> <http://purl.org/vocab/vann/usageNote> "xxx"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#ReliabilityDocument> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "xxx"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#ReliabilityDocument> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "ReliabilityDocument"@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#ShortData
<https://w3id.org/pink#ShortData> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#ShortData> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <https://w3id.org/pink#IntData> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#ShortData> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#seeAlso> <https://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema11-2/#short> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#ShortData> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "A data representing a 16-bit integer number."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#ShortData> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "ShortData"@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#Sign
<https://w3id.org/pink#Sign> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Sign> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#Entity> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Sign> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "A sign that stands for an entity."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Sign> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Sign"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Sign> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote> "A sign is a part of a triadic semiotic (meaning-making) process, where an 'interpreter' connects a 'sign' to an entity (called 'referent')."@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#Software
<https://w3id.org/pink#Software> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Software> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <https://w3id.org/pink#Data> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Software> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "All or part of the programs, procedures, rules, and associated documentation of an information processing system."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Software> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Software"@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#SsbdDimension
<https://w3id.org/pink#SsbdDimension> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#SsbdDimension> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#Entity> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#SsbdDimension> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Note this class redefined in PR https://github.com/PINK-project/PINK-annotation-schema/pull/15"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#SsbdDimension> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "SsbdDimension"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#SsbdDimension> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote> "The pink:SsbdDimension is an extension of the 'sustainability dimensions' defined by JRC." .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#SymbolicData
<https://w3id.org/pink#SymbolicData> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#SymbolicData> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <https://w3id.org/pink#Data> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#SymbolicData> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#seeAlso> <https://www.w3.org/TR/2012/REC-owl2-syntax-20121211/#Datatype_Maps> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#SymbolicData> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#seeAlso> <https://www.w3.org/TR/2012/REC-xmlschema11-2-20120405/#built-in-datatypes> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#SymbolicData> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "The class for entities which stands for a specific data format expressed using a symbolic encoding."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#SymbolicData> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "SymbolicData"@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#TierLevel
<https://w3id.org/pink#TierLevel> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#TierLevel> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#Entity> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#TierLevel> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Represent a tiered, iterative framework for evaluating chemical and material safety from early innovation to production."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#TierLevel> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "TierLevel"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#TierLevel> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote> "This approach typically involves a three-tier system-ranging from qualitative, early-stage, in silico, and in vitro screening to, finally, advanced, quantitative, in vivo testing."@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#TimeData
<https://w3id.org/pink#TimeData> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#TimeData> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <https://w3id.org/pink#SymbolicData> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#TimeData> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#seeAlso> <https://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema11-2/#time> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#TimeData> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "A symbolic data representing time. Format: hh:mm:ss (followed by an optional time zone offset, e.g. +01:00 for Central Europe)."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#TimeData> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "TimeData"@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#Toxicity
<https://w3id.org/pink#Toxicity> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Toxicity> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <https://w3id.org/pink#Sign> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Toxicity> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "The property or ability of a substance to cause harmful health effects."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Toxicity> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Toxicity"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Toxicity> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote> "The helth effects can strike a single cell, a group of cells, an organ system, or the entire body. A toxic effect may be visible damage, or a decrease in performance or function measurable only by a test."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Toxicity> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote> "Toxicity is always related to a given measurement procedure. Hence, the user is expected to define spesific subclasses defining the measurement procedure that the toxicity is measured according to."@en .
