# https://w3id.org/pink#economic
<https://w3id.org/pink#economic> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#economic> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://w3id.org/pink#SsbdDimension> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#economic> <http://purl.org/dc/terms/bibliographicCitation> "Caldeira et al. JRC Technical Report. Sage and Sustainable by Design chemicals and materials. EU Science Hub. doi:10.2760/487955. 2022" .
<https://w3id.org/pink#economic> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Aspects related to techno-economic feasibility, to operational costs, etc."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#economic> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "economic" .
<https://w3id.org/pink#economic> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote> "Note this class redefined in PR https://github.com/PINK-project/PINK-annotation-schema/pull/15"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#economic> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote> "There are important considerations to be made in the context of SSbD\nsuch as the 'availability' of raw materials, as chemicals/materials\ncannot be declared SSbD if the raw materials to produce them are not\nrenewable or are (very) scarce and extracted and processed in an\nunsustainable manner. Economic aspects play a role when there is a\nneed to rank chemicals and materials based on SSbD criteria (even if\nthey are not SSbD). However, mainly externalities consideration is at\nstake in a sustainability framework like the SSbD one."@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#environmental_systainability
<https://w3id.org/pink#environmental_systainability> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#environmental_systainability> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://w3id.org/pink#SsbdDimension> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#environmental_systainability> <http://purl.org/dc/terms/bibliographicCitation> "Caldeira et al. JRC Technical Report. Sage and Sustainable by Design chemicals and materials. EU Science Hub. doi:10.2760/487955. 2022" .
<https://w3id.org/pink#environmental_systainability> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "The ability to conserve natural resources and protect global ecosystems to support human health and wellbeing, within the limits of our Planet"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#environmental_systainability> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "environmental_systainability" .
<https://w3id.org/pink#environmental_systainability> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote> "Assessing environmental sustainability implies to assess the environmental impacts generated by\nchemicals/materials along the entire life cycle to move towards:\n\n  · A toxic-free environment as stated in the CSS (i.e. minimising the total toxicity footprint in terms\n    of ecotoxicity and human toxicity13 - at each stage of the production and consumption life cycle,\n    originated not only by the assessed chemical or material, but also by all the chemicals that are emitted\n    along the life cycle14) (EC, 2020a);\n  · A climate-neutral economy (i.e. minimising the emission of greenhouse gases along the life cycle)\n    (EC, 2019b);\n  · A resource efficient economy and a regenerative economy (i.e. using natural resources in a\n    sustainable manner, minimising inputs and waste generation, and providing more benefits than\n    burdens) (EC, 2020b);\n  · The reduction of biodiversity loss and the conservation of ecosystem functioning, addressing the\n    main drivers of structural and functional biodiversity loss (e.g. land use, climate change) (EC, 2020c);\n"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#environmental_systainability> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote> "Note this class redefined in PR https://github.com/PINK-project/PINK-annotation-schema/pull/15"@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#functionality
<https://w3id.org/pink#functionality> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#functionality> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://w3id.org/pink#SsbdDimension> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#functionality> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Note this class redefined in PR https://github.com/PINK-project/PINK-annotation-schema/pull/15"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#functionality> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "functionality" .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#safety
<https://w3id.org/pink#safety> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#safety> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://w3id.org/pink#SsbdDimension> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#safety> <http://purl.org/dc/terms/bibliographicCitation> "Caldeira et al. JRC Technical Report. Sage and Sustainable by Design chemicals and materials. EU Science Hub. doi:10.2760/487955. 2022" .
<https://w3id.org/pink#safety> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Human helth and environmental safety aspects of chemicals and materials."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#safety> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "safety" .
<https://w3id.org/pink#safety> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote> "In the context of chemicals assessment, safety could be referring to a\ncertain condition where a stressor (e.g. a chemical) is unlikely to\ncause any adverse effect to a receptor (e.g. humans and other\norganisms) (more related to intrinsic hazard properties of the\nstressor) or where a receptor is protected from risk (more related to\ncontrol measures or mechanisms to minimise exposure to the\nstressor). In any case, the term safe involves receptors, and with\nthat generally also requires the consideration of the contact\n(i.e. exposure) between stressors and receptors as addressed in a risk\nassessment context."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#safety> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote> "Note this class redefined in PR https://github.com/PINK-project/PINK-annotation-schema/pull/15"@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#social_systainability
<https://w3id.org/pink#social_systainability> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#social_systainability> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://w3id.org/pink#SsbdDimension> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#social_systainability> <http://purl.org/dc/terms/bibliographicCitation> "Caldeira et al. JRC Technical Report. Sage and Sustainable by Design chemicals and materials. EU Science Hub. doi:10.2760/487955. 2022" .
<https://w3id.org/pink#social_systainability> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "A globally agreed list of objectives and targets to be pursued for achieving sustainable development."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#social_systainability> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "social_sustainability" .
<https://w3id.org/pink#social_systainability> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote> "In the SDGs framework several Goals focus on social aspects,\ne.g. poverty eradication (SDG 1), food security (SDG 2), health (SDG 3),\neducation (SDG 4), gender equality (SDG 5), decent work (SDG 8),\nreduce inequalities (SDG 10), peace and justice (SDG 16)."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#social_systainability> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote> "Note this class redefined in PR https://github.com/PINK-project/PINK-annotation-schema/pull/15"@en .
